# 📘 React Notes (Components + Props + Map + Children)

## 🔹 Component

A component is a reusable function in React that returns UI. It helps in breaking the UI into smaller, manageable parts.

---

## 🔹 Props (Properties)

Props are used to pass data from a parent component to a child component. They make components dynamic and reusable.

---

## 🔹 Props Destructuring

Props destructuring is a way to directly extract values from props instead of using props.property. It makes the code cleaner and easier to read.

---

## 🔹 Default Props

Default props are fallback values assigned when no value is passed from the parent component. They ensure the component works even if some data is missing.

---

## 🔹 Children Prop

The children prop is a special prop in React that represents the content placed inside a component. It allows components to act as wrappers for other elements or components.

---

## 🔹 Array (Data Source)

An array is used to store multiple objects. In React, arrays are commonly used to hold data that needs to be displayed dynamically.

---

## 🔹 Object in Array

Each object inside an array represents a single item (e.g., a product). It contains properties like name, price, and description.

---

## 🔹 map() Function

The map() function is used to loop through an array and transform each item into a React component. It is used to render multiple components dynamically.

---

## 🔹 Spread Operator (...object)

The spread operator is used to pass all properties of an object as props to a component. It reduces repetition and makes the code cleaner.

---

## 🔹 Conditional Rendering

Conditional rendering is used to display UI based on a condition. It allows different outputs depending on the data.

---

## 🔹 Logical AND (&&)

The && operator is used to render something only if a condition is true. If the condition is false, nothing is displayed.

---

## 🔹 Ternary Operator

The ternary operator is used for conditional rendering with two outcomes. It works like an if-else statement.

---

## 🔹 Key Prop

The key prop is used to uniquely identify elements in a list. It helps React efficiently update and manage the UI.

---

## 🔹 Data Flow

React follows a one-way data flow, meaning data moves from parent to child components through props.

---

## 🔹 Dynamic UI

Dynamic UI means the interface changes based on data. Using map(), props, and conditions, React can render different outputs without changing the component structure.

---

## 🔹 Summary

In this project, an array of objects is used as data. The map() function loops through the data and renders a component for each item. Props pass the data into components, and conditional rendering controls how the UI appears. The Section component uses children to wrap and display multiple components inside it.


